  <p><strong>Diaspora note:</strong> You can initiate this step from abroad through a Ghanaian lawyer. You do not need to be physically present for company registration. However, you will need to provide notarized copies of your passport, proof of address, and (if applicable) a Ghana Card or proof of Ghanaian citizenship. Documents notarized abroad may need apostille certification depending on your country of residence.</p>

  <h2 id="step-2-gipc-registration">Step 2: GIPC Registration</h2>

  <p>With your Certificate of Incorporation in hand, you can now apply to the Ghana Investment Promotion Centre. This is where the capital requirements become real.</p>

  <p><strong>The application package:</strong></p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>GIPC application form:</strong> Available from the GIPC office (Airport City, Accra) or downloadable from their website. The form requires detailed information about the enterprise, shareholders, capital structure, and business plan.</li>
    <li><strong>Certificate of Incorporation:</strong> Original or certified true copy from the Registrar General.</li>
    <li><strong>Business plan:</strong> GIPC requires a business plan that describes the enterprise, its market, employment projections, and capital deployment schedule. This does not need to be a 50-page document, but it must be specific and credible. Generic plans are flagged.</li>
    <li><strong>Proof of capital:</strong> Bank statements showing inward remittance, customs documentation for imported equipment, or asset valuation reports for capital goods.</li>
    <li><strong>Tax Identification Number (TIN):</strong> Obtained from the Ghana Revenue Authority. Your lawyer or accountant typically handles this alongside company registration.</li>
    <li><strong>Environmental permits:</strong> If applicable to your sector (manufacturing, agro-processing, construction), you need an Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) permit before GIPC will process your application.</li>
    <li><strong>Passport copies of all foreign shareholders and directors.</strong></li>
  </ol>

  <p><strong>The registration fee:</strong> GIPC charges a registration fee that varies by sector and investment size. The fee structure is not prominently published and has changed multiple times. Budget GHS 5,000 to 15,000 ($455 to $1,370) for the GIPC registration fee itself. Your lawyer can confirm the current schedule before submission.</p>

  <p><strong>Processing time:</strong> GIPC officially states 5 business days for processing. In practice, the timeline is 2 to 6 weeks. The most common cause of delay is incomplete documentation. GIPC does not reject applications outright; they return them with a list of missing items. Each return-and-resubmit cycle adds 1 to 2 weeks.</p>

