    </table>
  </div>

  <p><strong>The bank account bottleneck:</strong> Opening a corporate bank account for a foreign-owned entity in Ghana now takes significantly longer than it did five years ago. Anti-money laundering regulations, Bank of Ghana compliance requirements, and enhanced due diligence for companies with foreign shareholders create a process that routinely takes 2 to 4 weeks. Some banks require an in-person visit by a director. Plan for this; you cannot operate without a functioning bank account, and you cannot demonstrate capital deployment without one.</p>

  <h2 id="diaspora-pitfalls">Diaspora-Specific Pitfalls</h2>

  <p>The following patterns emerge repeatedly among diaspora founders navigating GIPC registration. These are not theoretical risks; they are documented failure modes.</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 1: Treating Ghana entry as homecoming, not due diligence.</strong> Diaspora founders who return with emotional attachment to "giving back" consistently underestimate the bureaucratic and operational complexity. GIPC registration is a legal and financial process, not a cultural reconnection. Treat every interaction, every document, and every timeline as a business transaction requiring verification. (Source: Diaspora Lesson DL-010.)</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 2: Using a nominee structure to avoid capital requirements.</strong> Some diaspora founders register the company in a Ghanaian relative's name to avoid the $200,000 threshold. This creates three serious risks: you have no legal ownership of the business you funded; the nominee can sell, pledge, or encumber the company without your consent; and if the relationship deteriorates, you have no legal recourse. Nominee structures are the single most common source of diaspora founder disputes in Ghana.</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 3: Relying on the amendment bill to lower your costs.</strong> Founders who delay registration because "the $200,000 requirement is about to be removed" have been waiting since the bill was first proposed. Legislative timelines in Ghana are unpredictable. The bill lapsed once already. Do not build your business plan around unenacted legislation. (See: Failure Pattern FP-004.)</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 4: Choosing the cheapest lawyer.</strong> GIPC registration is a specialized process. A general-practice lawyer who "knows someone at GIPC" is not the same as a corporate lawyer who handles foreign investment registrations regularly. The cost difference between a GHS 2,000 generalist and a GHS 8,000 specialist is trivial compared to the cost of a rejected application, a 3-month delay, or a structurally flawed company registration.</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 5: Underestimating the bank account process.</strong> You cannot demonstrate capital deployment without a functioning corporate bank account. You cannot open a bank account without a Certificate of Incorporation. And the bank's due diligence process for foreign-owned entities is slow and document-heavy. Sequence this correctly: start the bank account process the same week you receive your Certificate of Incorporation.</p>

  <p><strong>Pitfall 6: Ignoring land title risks.</strong> If your business requires land, the land acquisition process in Ghana deserves its own guide. For now: never purchase land without a lawyer conducting a Lands Commission search. Never rely on family land promises without formal documentation. Never assume that a "chief's consent" is equivalent to legal title. Land disputes have destroyed more diaspora investments than any other single factor.</p>

